Chicago, Ill. Mar 24, 1894
My dear Herron,
That letter must be as if it had never been written. So shall it be to me. and I cannot allow it to stand between us over night. For the very many and serious "inductions" which were drawn more hastily than your disclaimer of them. You must surely feel that you have the utmost provocation in the "facts" you allege without the statement of one of them.
May not justice, not to say friendship have been better served had you reserved the farther until you could have stated the latter?

You may be assured, however, that you have no facts ^ in the premisses that you did not receive
at first hand from me directly. Hairy had no previous experience in probationary friendship, I never once
raised the question that our personal relations could be touched by either the fearless statement of facts which
I reported to you from Princeton. or the frank ^ and friendly criticism of your printed opinions - which the
form of some of them certainly invites. Between one's own corrections and anothers there can be no choice.
but, for the first time in my life, I am accused of choosy self instead of a friend and place and position which
I have neither sought nor thought of - instead of truth and service. If I did not think this unworthy of the man
whose spirit I have ever confided in and never failed to defend,mm?bal silence would have been my only
rejoinder. But believing that I know you better than you do me, I subscribe myself now and will until you deem
it unfriendly [to] do so    your Friend   Graham Taylor -

 Dear Arthur.
  My typist is off-duty at Raimia [sic - Ravinia?], So I send this copy from the point of the pen, to save time.
The National & International significance of this Conference is so pronounced, especially in

view of the impending diplomacy for the reduction of armaments, as to warrant emphasis upon 
what was said by speakers of such eminence.

 Except the German Ambassador's name I see nothing superfluous in this copy to its ^ social

interpretation of the significance of the occasion, though you may measure space as more
significant to the make-up.

 Our local press gave scant and inconspicuous publicity to this notable occasion, while Tribune

cartoons of Hearst's comments played-up their worst against pacifist pusillanimity!

  Yrs  Graham Taylor

Social Work has no higher quest for the solution of its problems and the  fulfilment [sic] of its purposes than

the presentation of friendships across racial, ^ economic and national lines on its local and country-wide fields.
The call of the World Alliance for International Friendship through the churches to its Sixteenth Good Will
Congress, held at Chicago Nov 10-12 ^ therefore was addressed to Social Workers as well as to church workers
of all  religious fellowships. The response in attendance from all parts of the country was notable for the 
widely representative personnel and for the fact of the preponderance of men, and of those from the middle and
younger ages of manhood and womanhood. Foremost among the guests of honor to be invited to the speakers table
was Miss Jane Addams. With her, Miss Mary McDowell served on the resolutions Committee, while ^ in the
Cooperating committee were such out-

 The interweaving of the diverse interests involved in the discussion of disarmament, peace and prosperity was even

more distinctive of the program than its distinguished spokesmen. The racial factors in the problem of international
peace were seem to be Russia's economic reasons for opposing wars while they would interfere with its five year plan:
